'''''Rubik, the Amazing Cube''''' is a 30-minute [[Saturday-morning cartoon|Saturday morning animated series]] based on the puzzle created by [[Ernő Rubik]], produced by [[Ruby-Spears|Ruby-Spears Enterprises]] and broadcast as part of ''[[Pac-Man (TV series)|The Pac-Man]]/Rubik, the Amazing Cube Hour'' block on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] from September 10, to December 10, 1983. The Rubik half hour was broadcast in reruns as a standalone series on ABC from May 4 to August 31, 1985.<ref>
{{cite book| last=Erickson| first=Hal| title=Television Cartoon Shows: An Illustrated Encyclopedia, 1949 -2003, The Shows M-Z (Volume 2)| publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]| edition=2nd | location=Jefferson, N.C.| year=2005| pages=600, 691| isbn=978-0786422562}}</ref>

The program features a magic [[Rubik's Cube]] named Rubik who can fly through the air and has other special powers. Rubik can only come alive when the colored squares on his sides had been matched up. The voice of Rubik, [[Ron Palillo]], told ''[[TV Guide]]'' in 1983 that for the role, he spoke very slowly and then technicians sped up the tapes and raised the pitch. Palillo said Rubik's giggle is very different from the trademark laugh of Horshack, his character on the TV series ''[[Welcome Back, Kotter]]'', and that it is pretty "for an inanimate object".<ref>{{cite journal | date=November 5, 1983| title=Palillo's Puzzled| journal=[[TV Guide]]| volume=31| issue=45| page=78 | issn=0039-8543}}</ref>

==Premise==
Rubik had fallen out of the stagecoach of an evil magician, who became the main villain of the series. Rubik helped Carlos, Lisa, and Reynaldo Rodriguez, in foiling the magician’s attempts to recover Rubik.  Once, Rubik was recovered by a detective who was a relative of the magician, but then decided the children should keep Rubik as the magician would use him for evil and selfish purposes.

Outside of the evil magician, episodes usually dealt with more normal adversaries, such as when the eldest son had run afoul of a bully who had thwarted his efforts to gain a potential girlfriend, while at the same time the bully was making himself appear decent to the girl.  Rubik worked in secret to expose the bully’s true brutal personality in front of the girl.

For dramatic purposes, the cube was easily fully scrambled (such as by being dropped or grabbed by the family dog, and at least once Rubik scrambled himself) and usually solved quickly by the Rodriguez children, although in stressful circumstances it took them longer. When scrambled, Rubik can only be heard making low-key gibberish and sometime can be heard saying, "Help."

==Cast==
* [[Ron Palillo]] – Rubik
* [[Michael Bell (actor)|Michael Bell]] – Reynaldo Rodriguez
* Jennifer Fajardo – Lisa Rodriguez
* [[Michael Saucedo]] – Carlos Rodriguez
* Angela Moya – Marla

Additional voices: [[Jack DeLeon]], Alan Dinehart, [[Laurie Faso]], [[Takayo Fischer]], [[Bob Holt (actor)|Bob Holt]], [[Tress MacNeille]], Tysun McMullan, [[Neil Ross]], [[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]], [[Janet Waldo]], [[Alan Young]]

==Theme music==
In keeping with the Hispanic flavor of the show, the theme song was sung by [[Puerto Rico|Puerto Rican]] boy band [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]]. Featured in the song were Johnnny Lozada, Ricky Melendez, Charlie Masso, Ray Reyes and Roy Rossello.

